Detailed Description

An interface for encapsulating the methods for outputting values for a record from the Collector.

No exceptions are defined here: if something goes wrong, the preferred exceptions are ClassCastException or TransformerException. (TransformerException is for Serializable, but makes a lot of sense in this case also).

This interface contains two capabilities:

  • Record outputting
    • startRecord
    • outputXxx (repeated) for the fields
    • endRecord
  • Acknowledgment synchronization
    • commitTimerExpired
    • getLastSeqNoToAck
    • processDataSeqNoAck

Acknowledgment synchronization is to ensure that the ConnectionThread does not send back an ACK until a record is actually committed. Just because a record has been output doesn't mean that it has been properly persisted. So, there must be a communication between the outputter and the connection thread. This communication is done by getLastSeqNoToAck. The triggering of an ACk can be done either by the connection thread (calling commitTimerExpired) or by the outputter (calling back to the connection thread via processDataSeqNoAck

The caller must guarantee that the sequence will always be

  1. startRecord
  2. outputXxx (repeated)
  3. endRecord

The calls to outputXxx can contain any template at all; if you need to set things up for multiple kinds of output, then you should do that in the constructor (that is, get the fields and template information from CollectorConfig).

Calls to isValidLastSeqNoToAck and getLastSeqNoToAck can happen at any time. It is the responsibility of the implementor to make these thread safe (this includes being thread safe in a call to startRecord or endRecord).

The sequence number to startRecord is used to indicate which records have been committed.

There are two ways of communicating between the connection thread and the outputter (at least one must be provided; both can be if desired):

  1. At regular intervals the connection thread can request the last persisted sequence number.
  2. Whenever the outputter has reached a checkpoint, it can tell the connection thread. This is done with the the object passed to registerProcessDataSeqNoAck.

If you wish to allow the connection thread to query the last record successfully committed, you must use the the isValidLastSeqNoToAck and getLastSeqNoToAck methods. The connection calls these like this:
if (outputter.isValidLastSeqNoToAck()) {
  lastSeqNo = outputter.getLastSeqNoToAck();
  send ACK to transmitter
}

Whenever records are committed, you should have isValidLastSeqNoToAck return true, with the sequence number returned by getLastSeqNoToAck.

Before calling startRecord for the first time, the connection thread will call registerProcessDataSeqNoAck. This gives an object which implements a single method: rocessDataSeqNoAck#processDataSeqNoAck. Whenever the outputter reaches a commit point, it can call this method.

(Note that the connection thread may call registerProcessDataSeqNoAck with a parameter of null ... this is used to deregister the callback.)

If you use this second method, you can either always have isValidLastSeqNoToAck always return false; or you can have it return true</true> and give the committed seequence number as the result from getLastSeqNoToAck.

void com::xacct::CRANE::collector::CollectorOutputter::commitTimerExpired (   ) 
 

The caller thread may have a timer for forcing a commit: it calls this method whenever the timer expires. The behavior on this should be non-blocking. The outputter should attempt to commit as much as it can, in expectation of very soon being asked about the next commited sequence number. It can, if it wants, call the method given by registerProcessDataSeqNoAck, but this is not necessary.

Implemented in com::xacct::CRANE::collector::CsvOutputter, com::xacct::CRANE::collector::DedupSummaryOutputter, and com::xacct::CRANE::collector::NullOutputter.

long com::xacct::CRANE::collector::CollectorOutputter::getLastSeqNoToAck (   ) 
 

Get the sequence number of the last record that has been properly persisted. If newSeqNoToAck would return false, the value from this call is undefined.

boolean com::xacct::CRANE::collector::CollectorOutputter::isValidLastSeqNoToAck (   ) 
 

Test whether a call to getLastSeqNoToAck will give a valid result. Typically, this will be false until the first record has been properly persisted, then true thereafter. It is the caller's responsibility to deal with multiple calls to getLastSeqNoToAck; the test is simply for validity, not whether there is a new value.

See the note on thread safety for this interface.

Returns:
true if the call to newSeqNoToAck will generate a new value from any previous call
See also:
getLastSeqNoToAck

void com::xacct::CRANE::collector::CollectorOutputter::registerProcessDataSeqNoAck (  ProcessDataSeqNoAck  processDataSeqNoAck  ) 
 

For cases where the outputter can tell when an acknowledgment should be done, a "callback". The outputter can completely ignore this. If it uses this, it may choose to always have isValidLastSeqNoToAck return false. This routine may only be called before a startRecord or after a endRecord (that is, when an output record is not being built up).

Parameters:
processDataSeqNoAck the class for handling acknowledgments ... may be null, which causes "deregistration"
See also:
isValidLastSeqNoToAck

Implemented in com::xacct::CRANE::collector::CsvOutputter, com::xacct::CRANE::collector::DedupSummaryOutputter, and com::xacct::CRANE::collector::NullOutputter.

int  transmitterPort,
String  transmitterVendorString,
Date  transmitterBootTime,
long  seqNo,
int  sessionId,
int  templateId
) 
 

Prepare to output a record. The parameters given here will be active until endRecord is called.

See the note on thread safety for this interface.

Parameters:
transmitterAddress the transmitter's address (for this connection).
transmitterPort the transmitter's data port (for this connection) as negotiated by the version negotiation messages or (if that failed) by the configuration.
transmitterVendorString the transmitter's vendor string (for this connection), as returned by the GET SESS RSP message.
transmitterBootTime the transmitter's boot time (for this connection), as returned by the START ACK message.
seqNo the sequence number of the record. Usually, this increases each time, but there may be occasions when the sequence number starts back at a lower value or skips.
sessionId 
templateId
